.TH "STATS\-COLLECT\-START" "1" "" ""
.SH Command \f[I]\[aq]start\[aq]\f[R]
Start collecting statistics.
Run the \f[I]COMMAND\f[R] on the SUT and collect statistics while it
runs.
The \f[I]COMMAND\f[R] string may include placeholders in \f[CR]{}\f[R]
braces that will be substituted with actual values:
\f[CR]{HOSTNAME}\f[R], \f[CR]{USERNAME}\f[R], \f[CR]{PRIVKEY}\f[R],
\f[CR]{OUTDIR}\f[R], \f[CR]{REPORTID}\f[R], \f[CR]{STATS}\f[R],
\f[CR]{PIPE_PATH}\f[R].
.SS General options
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R]
Show this help message and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\-q\f[R]
Be quiet (print only important messages like warnings).
.TP
\f[B]\-d\f[R]
Print debugging information.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-debug\-modules\f[R] \f[I]MODNAME[,MODNAME1,...]\f[R]
Print debugging information only from the specified modules.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-force\-color\f[R]
Force colorized output even if the output stream is not a terminal (adds
ANSI escape codes).
.TP
\f[B]\-H\f[R] \f[I]HOSTNAME\f[R], \f[B]\-\-host\f[R] \f[I]HOSTNAME\f[R]
The hostname of the system under test (SUT).
The command will be executed on this system using SSH, instead of
running it locally.
If not specified, the command will be run locally.
.TP
\f[B]\-U\f[R] \f[I]USERNAME\f[R], \f[B]\-\-username\f[R] \f[I]USERNAME\f[R]
Name of the user to use for logging into the remote host over SSH.
By default, look up the user name in SSH configuration files.
If not found, use the current user name.
.TP
\f[B]\-K\f[R] \f[I]PRIVKEY\f[R], \f[B]\-\-priv\-key\f[R] \f[I]PRIVKEY\f[R]
Path to the private SSH key for logging into the remote host.
If not specified, keys configured for the host in SSH configuration
files (e.g.
\f[CR]\[ti]/.ssh/config\f[R]) are used.
If no keys are configured there, standard key files (e.g.
\f[CR]\[ti]/.ssh/id_rsa\f[R]) and the SSH agent are tried.
.SS Statistics collection options
.TP
\f[B]\-\-time\-limit\f[R] \f[I]LIMIT\f[R]
The time limit for statistics collection, after which the collection
will stop if the command (given as a positional argument) has not
finished executing.
Specify time value in minutes, or use one of the following specifiers: d
\- days, h \- hours, m \- minutes, s \- seconds.
For example, \[aq]\-\-time\-limit=1h 30m\[aq] means 1 hour and 30
minutes.
.TP
\f[B]\-o\f[R] \f[I]OUTDIR\f[R], \f[B]\-\-outdir\f[R] \f[I]OUTDIR\f[R]
Path to the directory to save the results at.
By default the results are stored in a directory named after the report
ID in the current directory.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-reportid\f[R] \f[I]REPORTID\f[R]
Report ID which will serve as an identifier for this run.
By default report ID is the current date, prefixed with the remote host
name in case the \[aq]\-H\[aq] option was used:
\f[CR][hostname\-]YYYYMMDD\f[R].
For example, \[dq]20150323\[dq] is a report ID for a run made on March
23, 2015.
The allowed characters are: ASCII alphanumeric, \[aq]\-\[aq],
\[aq].\[aq], \[aq],\[aq], \[aq]_\[aq], and \[aq]\[ti]\[aq].
.TP
\f[B]\-\-stats\f[R] \f[I]STATS\f[R]
Comma\-separated list of statistics to collect.
By default, only \[aq]turbostat, sysinfo\[aq] statistics are collected.
Use \[aq]all\[aq] to collect all possible statistics.
Use \[aq]\-\-stats=\[dq]\[dq]\[aq] or \[aq]\-\-stats=\[dq]none\[dq]\[aq]
to disable statistics collection.
You can also specify the statistics you do not want to collect by
pre\-pending the \[aq]!\[aq] symbol.
For example, \[aq]all,!turbostat\[aq] collects all statistics supported
by the SUT, except for turbostat.
Use \[aq]\-\-list\-stats\[aq] to get the full list of supported
statistics and their descriptions.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-stats\-intervals\f[R] *STATS_INTERVALS*
Statistics collection intervals as a comma\-separated list, e.g.
\[aq]acpower:5,turbostat:10\[aq] to collect SUT power consumption every
5 seconds and turbostat data every 10 seconds.
Use \[aq]\-\-list\-stats\[aq] to get the default interval values.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-list\-stats\f[R]
Print information about the statistics \[aq]stats\-collect\[aq] can
collect and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-report\f[R]
Generate an HTML report for collected results after the collection is
done (same as calling \[aq]stats\-collect report\[aq] with default
arguments).
.TP
\f[B]\-\-cmd\-local\f[R]
Run the \f[I]COMMAND\f[R] on the local host instead of on the SUT
(\f[I]HOSTNAME\f[R]).
This is useful for client/server workloads where the SUT runs the server
and the local host runs the client.
.TP
\f[B]\-P\f[R] \f[I]PIPE\f[R]PATH\f[I], \f[BI]\-\-pipe\-path\f[I] \f[R]PIPE\f[I]PATH\f[R]
Path to the named pipe where the executed command will write labels to
(on \f[I]HOSTNAME\f[R]).
Use the special keyword \[dq]auto\[dq] to instruct
\[aq]stats\-collect\[aq] to automatically create a named pipe in the
temporary directory (use the \f[CR]{PIPE_PATH}\f[R] placeholder in the
workload\[aq]s command line to get the path in this case).
No named pipe is created by default.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-pipe\-timeout\f[R] *PIPE_TIMEOUT*
The longest allowed interval between named pipe input lines.
The \[aq]stats\-collect\[aq] tool exits with an error if the interval
exceeds *PIPE_TIMEOUT*.
The default is 5 minutes.
Specify time value in minutes, or use one of the following specifiers: d
\- days, h \- hours, m \- minutes, s \- seconds.
For example, \[aq]\-\-pipe\-timeout=1m 20s\[aq] means 1 minute and 20
seconds.
.TP
\f[B]cmd\f[R] \f[I]CMD [CMD ...]\f[R]
The command to run on the SUT during statistics collection.
If \f[I]HOSTNAME\f[R] is provided, the tool will run the command on that
host (unless \[aq]\-\-cmd\-local\[aq] was specified).
Otherwise the tool will run the command on \[aq]localhost\[aq].
The command may include placeholders in \f[CR]{}\f[R] braces that will
be substituted with actual values.
The supported placeholders are \f[CR]{HOSTNAME}\f[R],
\f[CR]{USERNAME}\f[R], \f[CR]{PRIVKEY}\f[R], \f[CR]{OUTDIR}\f[R],
\f[CR]{REPORTID}\f[R], \f[CR]{STATS}\f[R], \f[CR]{PIPE_PATH}\f[R].
